SP  - 839
EP  - 865
VL  - 58
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1540-6261.00548
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT The Federal Reserve sets targets for interest rates which it enforces through direct market intervention. These targets are changed periodically. In this paper, we develop a term structure model in which the short rate is subject to a control which keeps it close to a target which changes from time to time. The probability of target changes is not constant in the model, but changes as a function of observables. The model performs well at explaining the shifts in the yield curve that accompany target changes.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Excessive Dollar Debt: Financial Development and Underinsurance
AU  - Caballero, Ricardo J.
AU  - Krishnamurthy, Arvind
Y1  - 2003/04/01
PY  - 2003
DA  - 2003/04/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1540-6261.00549
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 867
EP  - 893
VL  - 58
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1540-6261.00549
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT We propose that the limited financial development of emerging markets is a significant factor behind the large share of dollar-denominated external debt present in these markets. We show that when financial constraints affect borrowing and lending between domestic agents, agents undervalue insuring against an exchange rate depreciation. Since more of this insurance is present when external debt is denominated in domestic currency rather than in dollars, this result implies that domestic agents choose excessive dollar debt. We also show that limited financial development reduces the incentives for foreign lenders to enter emerging markets. The retarded entry reinforces the underinsurance problem.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Wealth Effects of Repurchases on Bondholders
AU  - Maxwell, William F.
AU  - Stephens, Clifford P.
Y1  - 2003/04/01
PY  - 2003
DA  - 2003/04/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1540-6261.00550
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 895
EP  - 919
VL  - 58
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1540-6261.00550
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Prior research has documented positive abnormal stock returns around the announcements of repurchase programs; several explanations of these returns have been suggested, including signaling, free cash flow, and wealth redistributions. This study analyzes abnormal stock, bond, and firm returns around repurchase announcements to examine these hypotheses. We find evidence consistent with both signaling and wealth redistribution. The loss to bondholders is a function of the size of the repurchase, and the risk of the firm's debt. We also find that bond ratings are twice as likely to be downgraded as upgraded after the announcement of the repurchase program.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Investor Protection and Firm Liquidity
AU  - Brockman, Paul
AU  - Chung, Dennis Y.
Y1  - 2003/04/01
